This observation is in accordance with the findings by Hu et al, who proposed that the surfaces modulated with O and N dopants exhibit a stronger PL property whereas the surfaces decorated with O and Cl atoms exhibit better photocatalytic activity. This is because the surface containing O and Cl hereatoms could induce both upward and downward bending while the surface rich in N atoms could only create upward band bending. As illustrated in Fig. 6(b), the bands bending by Cl and O dopants would create a close loop of internal electric field (E

                           in
                        ) which accelerates the charge transfer and promotes spatial separation of electron-hole pairs [154]. In addition, the chlorine-contained surface would change the surface energy trap to a position that favors the rapid generation of •OH radicals, which is the dominant species needed for the photodegradation of dye as demonstrated in Fig. 6(c) [155]. On the other hand, the strong electron affinity of amino groups could change the electron transition pathway and facilitate the radiative recombination of electron-hole in CQDs, hence resulted in excellent quantum efficiency [125,156]. The above facts are once again supported by Cheng et al. [157] who claimed that the photocatalytic efficiency of Cl-CQD in degrading MB and indigo carmine (IC) pollutants is greater than that of N-CQDs.
